\section*{Rules of assigning oxidation numbers}
1. The oxidation number of an atom is zero in a neutral substance that contains atoms of only one element. Thus, the atoms in $\mathrm{O}_{2}, \mathrm{O}_{3}, \mathrm{P}_{4}, \mathrm{~S}_{8}$, and aluminum metal all have an oxidation number of 0 .
2. The oxidation number of simple ions is equal to the charge on the ion. The oxidation number of sodium in the $\mathrm{Na}^{+}$ion is +1 , for example, and the oxidation number of chlorine in the $\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$ion is -1 .
3. The oxidation number of hydrogen is +1 when it is combined with a nonmetal as in $\mathrm{CH}_{4}, \mathrm{NH}_{3}, \mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}$, and HCl .
4. The oxidation number of hydrogen is -1 when it is combined with a metal as in. $\mathrm{LiH}, \mathrm{NaH}, \mathrm{CaH}_{2}$, and $\mathrm{LiAlH}_{4}$.
5. The metals in Group IA form compounds (such as $\mathrm{Li}_{3} \mathrm{~N}$ and $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{~S}$ ) in which the metal atom has an oxidation number of +1 .
6. The elements in Group IIA form compounds (such as $\mathrm{Mg}_{3} \mathrm{~N}_{2}$ and $\mathrm{CaCO}_{3}$ ) in which the metal atom has a +2 oxidation number.
7. Oxygen usually has an oxidation number of -2. Exceptions include molecules and polyatomic ions that contain $\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{O}$ bonds, such as $\mathrm{O}_{2}, \mathrm{O}_{3}$, $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{2}$.
8. The elements in Group VIIA often form compounds (such as $\mathrm{AlF}_{3}, \mathrm{HCl}$, and $\mathrm{ZnBr}_{2}$ ) in which the nonmetal has a - 1 oxidation number.
9. The sum of the oxidation numbers in a neutral compound is zero e.g. the sum of the oxidation number of all atoms in a molecule e.g. $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}=0$. $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}: 2(+1)+(-2)=0$
10. The sum of the oxidation numbers in a polyatomic/complex ion is equal to the charge on the ion. The oxidation number of the sulfur atom in the $\mathrm{SO}_{4}{ }^{2-}$ ion must be +6 , for example, because the sum of the oxidation numbers of the atoms in this ion must equal -2 .
$\mathrm{SO}_{4}{ }^{2-}:(+6)+4(-2)=-2$
11. Elements toward the bottom left corner of the periodic table are more likely to have positive oxidation numbers than those toward the upper right corner of the table. Sulfur has a positive oxidation number in $\mathrm{SO}_{2}$, for example, because it is below oxygen in the periodic table.
$\mathrm{SO}_{2}:(+4)+2(-2)=0$

