\subsection*{24.1 Elasticity}

Elasticity is the ability of a deformed material body to return to its original shape and size when the forces causing the deformation are removed. A body with this ability is said to behave (or respond) elastically. To a greater or lesser extent, most solid materials exhibit elastic behavior, but there is a limit to the magnitude of the force and the accompanying deformation within which elastic recovery is possible for any given material. This limit, called the elastic limit, is the maximum stress or force per unit area within a solid material that can arise before the onset of permanent deformation. Stresses beyond the elastic limit cause a material to yield or flow. For such materials the elastic limit marks the end of elastic behaviour and the beginning of plastic behaviour. For most brittle materials, stresses beyond the elastic limit result in fracture with almost no plastic deformation.

\subsection*{24.2 Surface tension}

Surface tension is a physical property equal to the amount of force per unit area necessary to expand the surface of a liquid. It is the tendency of a fluid surface to occupy the smallest possible surface area. Surface tension is a principal factor in capillary action. The addition of substances called surfactants can reduce the surface tension of a liquid. For example, adding detergent to water decreases its surface tension. While pepper sprinkled on water floats, pepper sprinkled on water with detergent will sink.

Surface tension forces are due to intermolecular forces between the liquid's molecules at the liquid's outer boundaries. The units of surface tension are either energy per unit area or force per unit length.

